article.headline: Detroit rallies from 15 down
article.linkText: Ford comes through as Shock edge Sun
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Cheryl Ford has her championship ring.
Now, she says, it's time for her father to get his.

The Detroit Shock forward hit a game-winning layup with 1.8
seconds left to lift the defending WNBA champs to a 74-73 victory
over the Connecticut Sun on Sunday.

The win snapped Detroit's three-game losing streak and came just
hours before tip-off of the NBA Finals between the Shock's
brethren, the Pistons, and Ford's father Karl Malone and his Los
Angeles Lakers. Seven months ago, she jumped into his arms at
courtside moments after the Shock beat the Los Angeles Sparks for
their first title.

"I just told him it's his turn now," Ford said. "He's got
four more wins to go. He really deserves it. He works hard every
year. I'm just proud of him to know he's still out there playing
and trying to get his ring."

Ford, who turned 23 on Sunday, turned in a strong inside game,
finishing with 14 points and 12 rebounds. The Shock (2-3)
outrebounded Connecticut 37-22, outscoring the Sun 42-24 in the
paint.

"I just kept thinking we can't lose again," Ford said. "We
just needed a `W.' I didn't care if it was ugly or pretty."

Swin Cash paced Detroit with 20 points and Deanna Nolan had 10
of her 19 in a 3-minute stretch late in the second half.

Connecticut (3-3) is winless against Detroit in their last seven
meetings including last year's Eastern Conference playoffs. Taj
McWilliams-Franklin led the Sun with 17 points and Wendy Palmer
added 15.

The Sun had a three-game winning streak coming into the game and
were playing for their third time in four days. They looked
anything but fatigued early on, shooting 60 percent in the first
half to build a 45-34 lead. Rookie guard Lindsay Whalen was 4-for-4
from the field, including two 3-pointers, and had 10 points at
halftime.

The Sun opened a 15-point lead with 17:34 left in the game, but
Ford and her teammates began to take control inside.

"I thought Connecticut played spectacular for a tremendous part
of the game," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "Our sheer will
is what won the game for us. I'm hoping for the last part of the
game we realized how important it is to play that hard and play
that focused."

Detroit outrebounded the Sun 23-11 in the second half and scored
15 points on second-chance baskets. Nolan also turned up the
intensity with her outside game, hitting four pullup jumpers off
screens with under 6 minutes to play. Her jumper with 4 minutes to
play gave the Shock a 64-63 lead, their first since 18:18 in the
first half.

"I didn't think I was aggressive enough in the first half,"
Nolan said. "Each night we have to be mentally focused for 40
minutes. We have to go out like it's a championship game."

Nykesha Sales of the Sun hit a leaner with 1:12 left and Whalen
added two free throws with 52 seconds left for a 73-70 lead.

Ford countered with an inside basket to pull Detroit within one
and the Sun turned it over under their basket on the next
possession. Nolan missed a jumper but teammate Elaine Powell
rebounded and found Ford in traffic on the baseline for the
game-winner.

"They killed us on the boards," Connecticut coach Mike
Thibault said. "We lost the physical battle. We had the game
won."

Sales and Whalen each had 14 points.

The Shock planned to stay in Connecticut on Sunday night and
watch the first game of the Pistons-Lakers series on television.
Ford had no qualms about her allegiance.

"I love the Pistons, they're my boys, but I love my dad even
more," Ford said. "He'll be there when everybody else is not."

She said Malone had a message for her before Sunday's game:
"Happy Birthday."
